    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "My Sub-Zero UC-15I ice indicator is flashing, what does it mean?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The UC-15I has a built-in safety shutoff that triggers in two conditions per Sub-Zero's service documentation: two consecutive maximum freeze+harvest cycles (about 55 minutes total) without dropping ice, or 120 continuous cycles, roughly 2 days, without the bin switch detecting a full bin. When one of those trips, the ice indicator flashes and the unit stops attempting to produce ice. Almost always a water-supply issue: closed shutoff valve (often behind the kickplate or in an adjacent cabinet), clogged water filter (Sub-Zero resets the filter counter every 8,000 cycles, press and hold CLEAN for 6 seconds to reset), frozen fill tube, or failed water inlet valve. We diagnose the water path in one visit."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What's the difference between clear ice (UC-15I) and nugget ice (UC-24CI)?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Completely different machines internally. The UC-15I makes clear gourmet cubes by running water slowly over a cold evaporator plate, mineral impurities fall back into circulation instead of freezing in, so the finished cube is crystal-clear. The UC-24CI makes nugget ice (chewable pellet ice, the kind served at good restaurants) by extruding soft-frozen flakes through a compression mechanism. The service profiles are different: clear ice machines see water pump, recirculation, evaporator-plate issues; nugget machines see auger motor, extruder, compression-mechanism issues. We service both, and we stock different parts for each platform."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "My UC-15I makes ice but won't harvest",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Classic harvest-cycle failure. The UC-15I freezes cubes on an evaporator plate for 25-30 minutes, then reverses refrigerant flow to briefly heat the plate and drop the ice sheet into the bin, this is the harvest phase. When harvest fails, cubes stay frozen to the plate and the machine stops making new ice. Three common causes: hot-gas harvest valve stuck ($245–$340), harvest thermostat failed ($125–$195), or control board harvest timer issue ($580–$820). Diagnosis requires watching at least one full cycle (about 35 minutes). We carry all three parts for single-visit resolution."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much does Sub-Zero ice maker repair cost?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Diagnostic is $89, waived with repair. Typical Sub-Zero ice maker repairs: water inlet valve $175–$265, harvest thermostat $125–$195, hot-gas harvest valve $245–$340, drain pump (UC-15IP/UC-15IPO models only) $285–$385, water filter $65 flat including install, condenser cleaning $145 flat, compressor start relay $95–$155, evaporator fan motor $320–$425, auger motor (UC-24CI nugget) $540–$720, main control board $580–$820. Integrated ice maker modules in refrigerator columns (BI-36U, IC-36FI, etc.) run $320–$450 for full module replacement."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "My ice cubes are hollow or not fully formed",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Water supply pressure issue. The UC-15I specification calls for 20-80 psi water pressure at the inlet; below 20 psi, the water pump can't fully wet the evaporator plate during freeze, and cubes come out hollow, thin, or white. Most common cause in LA: whole-house water filter cartridge past its service life, or the fridge-branch shutoff valve partially closed. We test pressure at the ice maker inlet with a gauge, trace the supply line back to find the restriction, and either replace the filter or the inlet valve depending on where the problem is. Second cause: cube-weight adjustment drifted, recalibration fixes it without parts."
        }
